  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A Resilient Community, A Transformed Future: Building Resilience in Textile Worker Communities</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Building Resilience in Textile Worker Communities Program is focused on providing communities, local government, and private sector partners involved in the textile industry in urban and peri-urban areas the tools to improve their resilience in the face of natural disasters and hazards. This is especially important in Jakarta and West Java as low-lying cities in these areas leave millions of people in the textile industry, as well as the factories they work  in, vulnerable to hazards. Critical issues which this program seeks to combat are: inadequate city infrastructure, particularly around water; inadequate waste management and transportation systems; natural hazards; migrant labor; and limited formalization of financing and savings schemes. 

Trainings in emergency response and resilience planning, along with collaboration with the local disaster management ministry (called BPBD), will allow Mercy Corps to build a replicable model for future community resilience efforts. This will be accomplished through technical assistance for communities to develop and submit proposals for local support in order to create longer-term program sustainability and engage of private sector partners.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To improve the resilience of urban and peri-urban populations vulnerable to hazards through strengthening the capacity of local communities, local government, and private sector actors to reduce risks.

Objective 1: Increased technical capacity of communities to plan for hazards and implement DRR programming  

Objective 2: Targeted vulnerable communities reduce their vulnerability by developing action plans and implementing pilot projects

Objective 3: Demonstrate successful community-driven DRR programming for future replication by communities using external funding sources (private and public)</narrative>
  </description>
